'''Geoffrey Olsen''' was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] artist from [[Merthyr Tydfil]], who spent time living in the [[Cotswolds]], [[Rome]], [[Florence]] and [[Miami]].<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref><ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/1916978.geoffrey_olsen/</ref><ref>http://www.geoffreyolsen.com/biography/</ref>

==Life and career==
Born Geoffrey Robert Olsen in [[Merthyr Tydfil]] on 4 November 1943. He attended Cyfarthfa Grammar School, set within [[Cyfarthfa Castle]],
the former mansion of iron-master family the [[William Crawshay II|Crawshays]]. He later attended [[Newport College of Art]], the [[University of the West of England|West Of England College Of Art]], [[Cardiff College of Art]] and the [[Academy of Fine Arts, Munich]].<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref><ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/1916978.geoffrey_olsen/</ref><ref>http://www.geoffreyolsen.com/biography/</ref>

From 1993 Olsen became the Principal Lecturer in Visual Arts at [[Oxford Brookes University]], becoming Senior Lecturer in Fine Art in 1997 - 2001. In 1996 he also became Artist in Residence at [[Florida International University]] before teaching on the MFA course in Visual Arts. From 1999-2000 he was artist in residence at [[Cheltenham Art Gallery & Museum]].<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref><ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/1916978.geoffrey_olsen/</ref><ref>http://www.geoffreyolsen.com/biography/</ref>

He was diagnosed with leukaemia in 2003, but continued to paint. He died in Gloucester 6 December 2007.<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref><ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/1916978.geoffrey_olsen/</ref><ref>http://www.geoffreyolsen.com/biography/</ref>

==Exhibiting==
Olsen exhibited widely from the 1970s including exhibitions at the [[MOMA, Wales|Museum of Modern Art, Wales]], the [[National Library of Wales]], the [[British School in Rome]] and [[Florida International University]]. His work was also included in a number of group exhibitions, including "Painting the Dragon" at the [[National Museum of Wales]], the "Wales Drawing Biennale 2000"  at the [[Glynn Vivian Art Gallery]], the 1992 [[National Eisteddfod of Wales]] in [[Aberystwyth]], the [[Museum of Modern Art, Oxford]], [[Ikon Gallery]], [[Camden Arts Centre]], the [[Corcoran Museum of Art]] and other locations in [[Europe]] and the [[USA]].<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref><ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/1916978.geoffrey_olsen/</ref><ref>http://www.geoffreyolsen.com/biography/</ref>

==Artwork==
Olsen<U+2019>s artwork uses [[Abstract Art|abstracted]] [[Geography|geographical]] forms and memory from the places he knew best, including [[Merthyr Tydfil]], the [[Cotswolds]], [[Rome]], [[Florence]] and [[Miami]].<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref><ref>http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/1916978.geoffrey_olsen/</ref><ref>http://www.geoffreyolsen.com/biography/</ref>
Together with painting, during his later life in Miami, he also worked on producing books in collaboration with the writer Jerome Fletcher<ref>http://www.poetrybeyondtext.org/fletcher.html</ref> using both hyper-text and conventional narratives.<ref>http://issuu.com/frostart/docs/geoffery_olsen_miami_paintings</ref>

Poet, art historian and critic [[Tony Curtis (Welsh poet)|Tony Curtis]] described his collaborative artist book with the bookbinder David Sellars, as "one of the outstanding artists' books of recent years". The book combined images of [[Florence]] alongside those of [[Merthyr Tydfil]], using laser prints, screen-printing and acrylic paint on [[Kh<U+0101>d<U+012B>]] paper.<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/geoffrey-olsen-original-and-energetic-painter-765306.html</ref>

His work is held in a number of collections including [[Cheltenham Art Gallery & Museum]], [[Russell-Cotes Art Gallery & Museum]], [[University of Southampton]] and [[Gloucestershire Royal Hospital|Gloucestershire Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/yourpaintings/paintings/running-the-white-tip-merthyr-16991</ref>

